</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Breast magnetic resonance (MR) imaging, because of its extremely high sensitivity in detecting invasive breast cancers, is sometimes used as a diagnostic tool to evaluate equivocal mammographic findings. However, breast MR imaging should never substitute for a complete diagnostic evaluation or for biopsy of suspected, localizable suspicious mammographic lesions, whenever possible. The modality’s high cost, in addition to only moderate specificity, mandate that radiologists use it sparingly and with discrimination for problematic mammographic findings. It is rare that the reality or significance of a noncalcified mammographic finding remains equivocal or problematic at diagnostic mammography evaluation, which usually includes targeted ultrasonography (US). There are several reasons for this infrequent occurrence: <i>(a)</i> an asymmetry may persist on diagnostic views but be visible only on craniocaudal or mediolateral oblique projections, precluding three-dimensional localization for US or biopsy, or a lesion may persist on some diagnostic spot views but dissipate or efface on others; <i>(b)</i> uncertainty may exist as to whether apparent change is clinically important or owing to technical factors such as compression or positioning differences; or <i>(c)</i> a lesion may be suspected but biopsy options are limited owing to lack of a US correlate and lesion inaccessibility for stereotactic biopsy, or biopsy of a vague or questionably real lesion has been attempted unsuccessfully. This article will discuss the indications for problem-solving MR imaging for equivocal mammographic findings, present cases illustrating appropriate and inappropriate uses of problem-solving MR imaging, and present false-positive and false-negative cases affecting the specificity of breast MR imaging.</div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2016</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2016150205">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2016150205">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150205/asset/images/large/rg.2016150205.fig1a.jpeg" height="919" width="474" aria-labelledby="fig1a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span>. Malignant asymmetry without US correlate in a 62-year-old woman with a history of right breast lumpectomy. <b>(a, b)</b> Patient presented with a new asymmetry (arrow) in the deep, slightly medial left breast on <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> view <b>(a)</b> at mammography, which is persistent on the <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> rolled lateral view <b>(b)</b> and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> spot compression view (not shown). <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> and <abbr title="mediolateral">ML</abbr> views, and targeted US evaluation, were all negative (not shown). <b>(c)</b> Breast MR imaging was recommended. Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted subtraction MR image shows a small enhancing mass corresponding to the mammographic equivocal one-view finding. Stage 1 invasive lobular cancer was diagnosed at MR imaging–guided core biopsy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150205&amp;id=fig1a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150205/asset/images/large/rg.2016150205.fig1b.jpeg" height="919" width="580" aria-labelledby="fig1b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span>. Malignant asymmetry without US correlate in a 62-year-old woman with a history of right breast lumpectomy. <b>(a, b)</b> Patient presented with a new asymmetry (arrow) in the deep, slightly medial left breast on <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> view <b>(a)</b> at mammography, which is persistent on the <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> rolled lateral view <b>(b)</b> and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> spot compression view (not shown). <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> and <abbr title="mediolateral">ML</abbr> views, and targeted US evaluation, were all negative (not shown). <b>(c)</b> Breast MR imaging was recommended. Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted subtraction MR image shows a small enhancing mass corresponding to the mammographic equivocal one-view finding. Stage 1 invasive lobular cancer was diagnosed at MR imaging–guided core biopsy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150205&amp;id=fig1b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150205/asset/images/large/rg.2016150205.fig1c.jpeg" height="576" width="797" aria-labelledby="fig1c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1c</span>. Malignant asymmetry without US correlate in a 62-year-old woman with a history of right breast lumpectomy. <b>(a, b)</b> Patient presented with a new asymmetry (arrow) in the deep, slightly medial left breast on <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> view <b>(a)</b> at mammography, which is persistent on the <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> rolled lateral view <b>(b)</b> and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> spot compression view (not shown). <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> and <abbr title="mediolateral">ML</abbr> views, and targeted US evaluation, were all negative (not shown). <b>(c)</b> Breast MR imaging was recommended. Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted subtraction MR image shows a small enhancing mass corresponding to the mammographic equivocal one-view finding. Stage 1 invasive lobular cancer was diagnosed at MR imaging–guided core biopsy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150205&amp;id=fig1c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150205/asset/images/large/rg.2016150205.fig2a.jpeg" height="739" width="549" aria-labelledby="fig2a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span>. Diagnostic uncertainty in a 42-year-old high-risk patient. <b>(a–c)</b> Mammograms show equivocal distortion on a left <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> view <b>(a)</b>, which is persistent on a spot <abbr title="mediolateral">ML</abbr> view <b>(b)</b> but not on a spot <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> view <b>(c)</b>. <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> view and US (not shown) were negative. MR imaging was recommended. <b>(d)</b> Maximum intensity projection (MIP) MR imaging results were negative. The patient has been without evidence of disease for more than 3 years.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150205&amp;id=fig2a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150205/asset/images/large/rg.2016150205.fig2b.jpeg" height="739" width="545" aria-labelledby="fig2b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span>. Diagnostic uncertainty in a 42-year-old high-risk patient. <b>(a–c)</b> Mammograms show equivocal distortion on a left <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> view <b>(a)</b>, which is persistent on a spot <abbr title="mediolateral">ML</abbr> view <b>(b)</b> but not on a spot <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> view <b>(c)</b>. <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> view and US (not shown) were negative. MR imaging was recommended. <b>(d)</b> Maximum intensity projection (MIP) MR imaging results were negative. The patient has been without evidence of disease for more than 3 years.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150205&amp;id=fig2b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150205/asset/images/large/rg.2016150205.fig2c.jpeg" height="739" width="756" aria-labelledby="fig2c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2c</span>. Diagnostic uncertainty in a 42-year-old high-risk patient. <b>(a–c)</b> Mammograms show equivocal distortion on a left <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> view <b>(a)</b>, which is persistent on a spot <abbr title="mediolateral">ML</abbr> view <b>(b)</b> but not on a spot <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> view <b>(c)</b>. <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> view and US (not shown) were negative. MR imaging was recommended. <b>(d)</b> Maximum intensity projection (MIP) MR imaging results were negative. The patient has been without evidence of disease for more than 3 years.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150205&amp;id=fig2c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150205/asset/images/large/rg.2016150205.fig2d.jpeg" height="467" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig2d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2d</span>. Diagnostic uncertainty in a 42-year-old high-risk patient. <b>(a–c)</b> Mammograms show equivocal distortion on a left <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> view <b>(a)</b>, which is persistent on a spot <abbr title="mediolateral">ML</abbr> view <b>(b)</b> but not on a spot <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> view <b>(c)</b>. <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> view and US (not shown) were negative. MR imaging was recommended. <b>(d)</b> Maximum intensity projection (MIP) MR imaging results were negative. The patient has been without evidence of disease for more than 3 years.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150205&amp;id=fig2d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150205/asset/images/large/rg.2016150205.fig3a.jpeg" height="1091" width="478" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span>. Subtle equivocal distortion in a 61-year-old woman at screening <abbr title="digital breast tomosynthesis">DBT</abbr> only. <b>(a)</b> Routine <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> view at mammography is negative. <b>(b, c)</b> <abbr title="digital breast tomosynthesis">DBT</abbr> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> view <b>(b)</b> shows subtle distortion (arrow), which looked improved but still possibly present (arrow) on a spot <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> tomosynthesis view <b>(c)</b>. The equivocal finding localized to the upper outer quadrant, according to the graphic localizer tool at <abbr title="digital breast tomosynthesis">DBT</abbr> and on a mammographic <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> view (not shown), but targeted US was negative. MR imaging was recommended. <b>(d)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted fat-suppressed MR image shows a small enhancing mass (arrow) correlating to the mammographic finding. <b>(e)</b> Repeat US demonstrated a US correlate (arrows) for core biopsy, which showed a stage 1 invasive ductal cancer.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150205&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150205/asset/images/large/rg.2016150205.fig3b.jpeg" height="1091" width="429" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span>. Subtle equivocal distortion in a 61-year-old woman at screening <abbr title="digital breast tomosynthesis">DBT</abbr> only. <b>(a)</b> Routine <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> view at mammography is negative. <b>(b, c)</b> <abbr title="digital breast tomosynthesis">DBT</abbr> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> view <b>(b)</b> shows subtle distortion (arrow), which looked improved but still possibly present (arrow) on a spot <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> tomosynthesis view <b>(c)</b>. The equivocal finding localized to the upper outer quadrant, according to the graphic localizer tool at <abbr title="digital breast tomosynthesis">DBT</abbr> and on a mammographic <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> view (not shown), but targeted US was negative. MR imaging was recommended. <b>(d)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted fat-suppressed MR image shows a small enhancing mass (arrow) correlating to the mammographic finding. <b>(e)</b> Repeat US demonstrated a US correlate (arrows) for core biopsy, which showed a stage 1 invasive ductal cancer.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150205&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150205/asset/images/large/rg.2016150205.fig3c.jpeg" height="1090" width="543" aria-labelledby="fig3c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3c</span>. Subtle equivocal distortion in a 61-year-old woman at screening <abbr title="digital breast tomosynthesis">DBT</abbr> only. <b>(a)</b> Routine <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> view at mammography is negative. <b>(b, c)</b> <abbr title="digital breast tomosynthesis">DBT</abbr> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> view <b>(b)</b> shows subtle distortion (arrow), which looked improved but still possibly present (arrow) on a spot <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> tomosynthesis view <b>(c)</b>. The equivocal finding localized to the upper outer quadrant, according to the graphic localizer tool at <abbr title="digital breast tomosynthesis">DBT</abbr> and on a mammographic <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> view (not shown), but targeted US was negative. MR imaging was recommended. <b>(d)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted fat-suppressed MR image shows a small enhancing mass (arrow) correlating to the mammographic finding. <b>(e)</b> Repeat US demonstrated a US correlate (arrows) for core biopsy, which showed a stage 1 invasive ductal cancer.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150205&amp;id=fig3c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150205/asset/images/large/rg.2016150205.fig3d.jpeg" height="495" width="899" aria-labelledby="fig3d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3d</span>. Subtle equivocal distortion in a 61-year-old woman at screening <abbr title="digital breast tomosynthesis">DBT</abbr> only. <b>(a)</b> Routine <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> view at mammography is negative. <b>(b, c)</b> <abbr title="digital breast tomosynthesis">DBT</abbr> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> view <b>(b)</b> shows subtle distortion (arrow), which looked improved but still possibly present (arrow) on a spot <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> tomosynthesis view <b>(c)</b>. The equivocal finding localized to the upper outer quadrant, according to the graphic localizer tool at <abbr title="digital breast tomosynthesis">DBT</abbr> and on a mammographic <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> view (not shown), but targeted US was negative. MR imaging was recommended. <b>(d)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted fat-suppressed MR image shows a small enhancing mass (arrow) correlating to the mammographic finding. <b>(e)</b> Repeat US demonstrated a US correlate (arrows) for core biopsy, which showed a stage 1 invasive ductal cancer.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150205&amp;id=fig3d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150205/asset/images/large/rg.2016150205.fig3e.jpeg" height="495" width="576" aria-labelledby="fig3e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3e</span>. Subtle equivocal distortion in a 61-year-old woman at screening <abbr title="digital breast tomosynthesis">DBT</abbr> only. <b>(a)</b> Routine <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> view at mammography is negative. <b>(b, c)</b> <abbr title="digital breast tomosynthesis">DBT</abbr> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> view <b>(b)</b> shows subtle distortion (arrow), which looked improved but still possibly present (arrow) on a spot <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> tomosynthesis view <b>(c)</b>. The equivocal finding localized to the upper outer quadrant, according to the graphic localizer tool at <abbr title="digital breast tomosynthesis">DBT</abbr> and on a mammographic <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> view (not shown), but targeted US was negative. MR imaging was recommended. <b>(d)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted fat-suppressed MR image shows a small enhancing mass (arrow) correlating to the mammographic finding. <b>(e)</b> Repeat US demonstrated a US correlate (arrows) for core biopsy, which showed a stage 1 invasive ductal cancer.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150205&amp;id=fig3e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150205/asset/images/large/rg.2016150205.fig4a.jpeg" height="1101" width="558" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span>. Differences in positioning in a 54-year-old woman with a strong family history of breast cancer. <b>(a, b)</b> Questionable posterior asymmetry (arrow) on mammographic <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> view <b>(a)</b>, persistent (arrow) on spot <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> view <b>(b)</b>, questionably developing versus positioned differently from prior <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> view (not shown), not identified on <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> view or at US (not shown). <b>(c)</b> MIP MR imaging results are negative. The patient is without evidence of disease for more than 2 years.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150205&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150205/asset/images/large/rg.2016150205.fig4b.jpeg" height="1101" width="667" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span>. Differences in positioning in a 54-year-old woman with a strong family history of breast cancer. <b>(a, b)</b> Questionable posterior asymmetry (arrow) on mammographic <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> view <b>(a)</b>, persistent (arrow) on spot <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> view <b>(b)</b>, questionably developing versus positioned differently from prior <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> view (not shown), not identified on <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> view or at US (not shown). <b>(c)</b> MIP MR imaging results are negative. The patient is without evidence of disease for more than 2 years.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150205&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150205/asset/images/large/rg.2016150205.fig4c.jpeg" height="480" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig4c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4c</span>. Differences in positioning in a 54-year-old woman with a strong family history of breast cancer. <b>(a, b)</b> Questionable posterior asymmetry (arrow) on mammographic <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> view <b>(a)</b>, persistent (arrow) on spot <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> view <b>(b)</b>, questionably developing versus positioned differently from prior <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> view (not shown), not identified on <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> view or at US (not shown). <b>(c)</b> MIP MR imaging results are negative. The patient is without evidence of disease for more than 2 years.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150205&amp;id=fig4c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150205/asset/images/large/rg.2016150205.fig5a.jpeg" height="1002" width="623" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span>. Differences in compression in a 61-year-old woman with prior left lumpectomy. <b>(a, b)</b> Mammographic <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> view <b>(a)</b> shows a small posterior-inferior asymmetry (thin arrow). Thick arrow = lumpectomy scar. Compared with the <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> view <b>(b)</b> from 2 years previously, there is subtle change from the earlier finding (arrow in <b>b</b>), questionably developing versus differences in compression and positioning. <b>(c)</b> Asymmetry persisted on an <abbr title="mediolateral">ML</abbr> view (arrow) and on spot compression (not shown), but a <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> view (not shown) was negative. Targeted US (presumed location triangulated from <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> and <abbr title="mediolateral">ML</abbr> views) was negative. MR imaging was recommended. <b>(d)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced T1-weighted fat-suppressed image shows an irregular enhancing mass (arrow) correlating with the mammographic asymmetry. MR imaging–guided core biopsy revealed recurrent invasive ductal cancer.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150205&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150205/asset/images/large/rg.2016150205.fig5b.jpeg" height="1002" width="601" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span>. Differences in compression in a 61-year-old woman with prior left lumpectomy. <b>(a, b)</b> Mammographic <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> view <b>(a)</b> shows a small posterior-inferior asymmetry (thin arrow). Thick arrow = lumpectomy scar. Compared with the <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> view <b>(b)</b> from 2 years previously, there is subtle change from the earlier finding (arrow in <b>b</b>), questionably developing versus differences in compression and positioning. <b>(c)</b> Asymmetry persisted on an <abbr title="mediolateral">ML</abbr> view (arrow) and on spot compression (not shown), but a <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> view (not shown) was negative. Targeted US (presumed location triangulated from <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> and <abbr title="mediolateral">ML</abbr> views) was negative. MR imaging was recommended. <b>(d)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced T1-weighted fat-suppressed image shows an irregular enhancing mass (arrow) correlating with the mammographic asymmetry. MR imaging–guided core biopsy revealed recurrent invasive ductal cancer.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150205&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150205/asset/images/large/rg.2016150205.fig5c.jpeg" height="903" width="539" aria-labelledby="fig5c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5c</span>. Differences in compression in a 61-year-old woman with prior left lumpectomy. <b>(a, b)</b> Mammographic <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> view <b>(a)</b> shows a small posterior-inferior asymmetry (thin arrow). Thick arrow = lumpectomy scar. Compared with the <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> view <b>(b)</b> from 2 years previously, there is subtle change from the earlier finding (arrow in <b>b</b>), questionably developing versus differences in compression and positioning. <b>(c)</b> Asymmetry persisted on an <abbr title="mediolateral">ML</abbr> view (arrow) and on spot compression (not shown), but a <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> view (not shown) was negative. Targeted US (presumed location triangulated from <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> and <abbr title="mediolateral">ML</abbr> views) was negative. MR imaging was recommended. <b>(d)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced T1-weighted fat-suppressed image shows an irregular enhancing mass (arrow) correlating with the mammographic asymmetry. MR imaging–guided core biopsy revealed recurrent invasive ductal cancer.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150205&amp;id=fig5c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150205/asset/images/large/rg.2016150205.fig5d.jpeg" height="903" width="686" aria-labelledby="fig5d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5d</span>. Differences in compression in a 61-year-old woman with prior left lumpectomy. <b>(a, b)</b> Mammographic <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> view <b>(a)</b> shows a small posterior-inferior asymmetry (thin arrow). Thick arrow = lumpectomy scar. Compared with the <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> view <b>(b)</b> from 2 years previously, there is subtle change from the earlier finding (arrow in <b>b</b>), questionably developing versus differences in compression and positioning. <b>(c)</b> Asymmetry persisted on an <abbr title="mediolateral">ML</abbr> view (arrow) and on spot compression (not shown), but a <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> view (not shown) was negative. Targeted US (presumed location triangulated from <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> and <abbr title="mediolateral">ML</abbr> views) was negative. MR imaging was recommended. <b>(d)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced T1-weighted fat-suppressed image shows an irregular enhancing mass (arrow) correlating with the mammographic asymmetry. MR imaging–guided core biopsy revealed recurrent invasive ductal cancer.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150205&amp;id=fig5d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150205/asset/images/large/rg.2016150205.fig6a.jpeg" height="1139" width="479" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span>. Difficulty of stereotactic biopsy for a posterior, low-density focal asymmetry in a 67-year-old woman. <b>(a, b)</b> Left <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <b>(a)</b> and left, laterally exaggerated CC (XCCL) <b>(b)</b> views show a new small focal asymmetry (arrow). US (not shown) was negative. The diagnostic radiologist considered the finding to be suspicious. However, stereotactic biopsy was considered to be technically challenging both due to the posterior location, and, more importantly, the vague, low-opacity appearance of the lesion, which would make accurate targeting difficult due to the reduced compression in the open window of the paddle and the likelihood of obscuration by lidocaine and/or blood. MR imaging was recommended for biopsy planning. <b>(c)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced T1-weighted fat-suppressed image shows nonmass enhancement correlating to the focal asymmetry. MR imaging guided–core biopsy showed stage 1 mixed invasive ductal and lobular cancer.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150205&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150205/asset/images/large/rg.2016150205.fig6b.jpeg" height="1139" width="518" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span>. Difficulty of stereotactic biopsy for a posterior, low-density focal asymmetry in a 67-year-old woman. <b>(a, b)</b> Left <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <b>(a)</b> and left, laterally exaggerated CC (XCCL) <b>(b)</b> views show a new small focal asymmetry (arrow). US (not shown) was negative. The diagnostic radiologist considered the finding to be suspicious. However, stereotactic biopsy was considered to be technically challenging both due to the posterior location, and, more importantly, the vague, low-opacity appearance of the lesion, which would make accurate targeting difficult due to the reduced compression in the open window of the paddle and the likelihood of obscuration by lidocaine and/or blood. MR imaging was recommended for biopsy planning. <b>(c)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced T1-weighted fat-suppressed image shows nonmass enhancement correlating to the focal asymmetry. MR imaging guided–core biopsy showed stage 1 mixed invasive ductal and lobular cancer.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150205&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150205/asset/images/large/rg.2016150205.fig6c.jpeg" height="1139" width="554" aria-labelledby="fig6c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6c</span>. Difficulty of stereotactic biopsy for a posterior, low-density focal asymmetry in a 67-year-old woman. <b>(a, b)</b> Left <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <b>(a)</b> and left, laterally exaggerated CC (XCCL) <b>(b)</b> views show a new small focal asymmetry (arrow). US (not shown) was negative. The diagnostic radiologist considered the finding to be suspicious. However, stereotactic biopsy was considered to be technically challenging both due to the posterior location, and, more importantly, the vague, low-opacity appearance of the lesion, which would make accurate targeting difficult due to the reduced compression in the open window of the paddle and the likelihood of obscuration by lidocaine and/or blood. MR imaging was recommended for biopsy planning. <b>(c)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced T1-weighted fat-suppressed image shows nonmass enhancement correlating to the focal asymmetry. MR imaging guided–core biopsy showed stage 1 mixed invasive ductal and lobular cancer.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150205&amp;id=fig6c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150205/asset/images/large/rg.2016150205.fig7a.jpeg" height="787" width="613" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span>. Focal asymmetry in a 56-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Left <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> view shows a focal asymmetry (arrow). <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> view showed the asymmetry in the upper breast (not shown). <b>(b)</b> US image shows an irregular mass (arrow) in the upper inner quadrant, a presumed correlate to the mammographic finding. US-guided core biopsy showed dense fibrous tissue and fibroadenomatoid change. <b>(c)</b> Postbiopsy <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> view shows a biopsy marker (thick arrow) medial and anterior to a focal asymmetry (thin arrow), suggesting possible mammographic-US discordance. <b>(d)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted fat-suppressed MR image shows mild nonsuspicious enhancement (thick arrow) just lateral to the biopsy marker (thin arrow). The reassuringly nonsuspicious MR imaging findings, which would be concordant with the pathologic findings, suggested that, rather than mammographic-US discordance (incorrect area having undergone US biopsy), the tissue marker had probably been displaced medially during biopsy. The patient was placed into surveillance and is without evidence of disease for greater than 3 years.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150205&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150205/asset/images/large/rg.2016150205.fig7b.jpeg" height="606" width="759" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span>. Focal asymmetry in a 56-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Left <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> view shows a focal asymmetry (arrow). <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> view showed the asymmetry in the upper breast (not shown). <b>(b)</b> US image shows an irregular mass (arrow) in the upper inner quadrant, a presumed correlate to the mammographic finding. US-guided core biopsy showed dense fibrous tissue and fibroadenomatoid change. <b>(c)</b> Postbiopsy <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> view shows a biopsy marker (thick arrow) medial and anterior to a focal asymmetry (thin arrow), suggesting possible mammographic-US discordance. <b>(d)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted fat-suppressed MR image shows mild nonsuspicious enhancement (thick arrow) just lateral to the biopsy marker (thin arrow). The reassuringly nonsuspicious MR imaging findings, which would be concordant with the pathologic findings, suggested that, rather than mammographic-US discordance (incorrect area having undergone US biopsy), the tissue marker had probably been displaced medially during biopsy. The patient was placed into surveillance and is without evidence of disease for greater than 3 years.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150205&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150205/asset/images/large/rg.2016150205.fig7c.jpeg" height="787" width="613" aria-labelledby="fig7c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7c</span>. Focal asymmetry in a 56-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Left <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> view shows a focal asymmetry (arrow). <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> view showed the asymmetry in the upper breast (not shown). <b>(b)</b> US image shows an irregular mass (arrow) in the upper inner quadrant, a presumed correlate to the mammographic finding. US-guided core biopsy showed dense fibrous tissue and fibroadenomatoid change. <b>(c)</b> Postbiopsy <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> view shows a biopsy marker (thick arrow) medial and anterior to a focal asymmetry (thin arrow), suggesting possible mammographic-US discordance. <b>(d)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted fat-suppressed MR image shows mild nonsuspicious enhancement (thick arrow) just lateral to the biopsy marker (thin arrow). The reassuringly nonsuspicious MR imaging findings, which would be concordant with the pathologic findings, suggested that, rather than mammographic-US discordance (incorrect area having undergone US biopsy), the tissue marker had probably been displaced medially during biopsy. The patient was placed into surveillance and is without evidence of disease for greater than 3 years.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150205&amp;id=fig7c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150205/asset/images/large/rg.2016150205.fig7d.jpeg" height="606" width="913" aria-labelledby="fig7d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7d</span>. Focal asymmetry in a 56-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Left <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> view shows a focal asymmetry (arrow). <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> view showed the asymmetry in the upper breast (not shown). <b>(b)</b> US image shows an irregular mass (arrow) in the upper inner quadrant, a presumed correlate to the mammographic finding. US-guided core biopsy showed dense fibrous tissue and fibroadenomatoid change. <b>(c)</b> Postbiopsy <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> view shows a biopsy marker (thick arrow) medial and anterior to a focal asymmetry (thin arrow), suggesting possible mammographic-US discordance. <b>(d)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted fat-suppressed MR image shows mild nonsuspicious enhancement (thick arrow) just lateral to the biopsy marker (thin arrow). The reassuringly nonsuspicious MR imaging findings, which would be concordant with the pathologic findings, suggested that, rather than mammographic-US discordance (incorrect area having undergone US biopsy), the tissue marker had probably been displaced medially during biopsy. The patient was placed into surveillance and is without evidence of disease for greater than 3 years.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150205&amp;id=fig7d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150205/asset/images/large/rg.2016150205.fig8a.jpeg" height="837" width="499" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span>. Calcifications in a 51-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral">ML</abbr> magnification view shows screen-detected clustered amorphous calcifications (arrow). They were also visible very posteriorly on an <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> view and not seen on a <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> view. The calcifications were assessed as probably benign, but MR imaging was recommended to “corroborate the benign assessment.” <b>(b)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced T1-weighted fat-suppressed MR image shows correlative nonmass enhancement (arrows), with slow persistent kinetics. MR imaging was not contributory in this case because lack of a correlate would not have excluded malignancy. Needle-localized excision showed <abbr title="ductal carcinoma in situ">DCIS</abbr>, three foci of invasive ductal cancer, and sclerosing adenosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150205&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150205/asset/images/large/rg.2016150205.fig8b.jpeg" height="837" width="425" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span>. Calcifications in a 51-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral">ML</abbr> magnification view shows screen-detected clustered amorphous calcifications (arrow). They were also visible very posteriorly on an <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> view and not seen on a <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> view. The calcifications were assessed as probably benign, but MR imaging was recommended to “corroborate the benign assessment.” <b>(b)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced T1-weighted fat-suppressed MR image shows correlative nonmass enhancement (arrows), with slow persistent kinetics. MR imaging was not contributory in this case because lack of a correlate would not have excluded malignancy. Needle-localized excision showed <abbr title="ductal carcinoma in situ">DCIS</abbr>, three foci of invasive ductal cancer, and sclerosing adenosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150205&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150205/asset/images/large/rg.2016150205.fig9a.jpeg" height="1065" width="486" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. Focal asymmetry in a 74-year-old woman. <b>(a, b)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <b>(a)</b> and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(b)</b> views show a new right focal asymmetry (arrows) in a fatty breast. US was equivocal, showing a possible correlate thought to be too vague for accurate targeting for US-guided core biopsy. MR imaging was recommended. <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted fat-suppressed image shows nonmass enhancement (arrows) correlating to the mammographic finding. In this case, MR imaging was unnecessary because the mammographic finding was new, localizable in three dimensions, and suspicious. The mammographic finding was amenable to stereotactic biopsy; the lesion was well visualized, being moderately dense in a predominantly fat-density background, and not too posterior for positioning. Stereotactic biopsy was performed, showing <abbr title="ductal carcinoma in situ">DCIS</abbr> with microinvasion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150205&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150205/asset/images/large/rg.2016150205.fig9b.jpeg" height="1065" width="479" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span>. Focal asymmetry in a 74-year-old woman. <b>(a, b)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <b>(a)</b> and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(b)</b> views show a new right focal asymmetry (arrows) in a fatty breast. US was equivocal, showing a possible correlate thought to be too vague for accurate targeting for US-guided core biopsy. MR imaging was recommended. <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted fat-suppressed image shows nonmass enhancement (arrows) correlating to the mammographic finding. In this case, MR imaging was unnecessary because the mammographic finding was new, localizable in three dimensions, and suspicious. The mammographic finding was amenable to stereotactic biopsy; the lesion was well visualized, being moderately dense in a predominantly fat-density background, and not too posterior for positioning. Stereotactic biopsy was performed, showing <abbr title="ductal carcinoma in situ">DCIS</abbr> with microinvasion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150205&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150205/asset/images/large/rg.2016150205.fig9c.jpeg" height="540" width="884" aria-labelledby="fig9c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9c</span>. Focal asymmetry in a 74-year-old woman. <b>(a, b)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <b>(a)</b> and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(b)</b> views show a new right focal asymmetry (arrows) in a fatty breast. US was equivocal, showing a possible correlate thought to be too vague for accurate targeting for US-guided core biopsy. MR imaging was recommended. <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted fat-suppressed image shows nonmass enhancement (arrows) correlating to the mammographic finding. In this case, MR imaging was unnecessary because the mammographic finding was new, localizable in three dimensions, and suspicious. The mammographic finding was amenable to stereotactic biopsy; the lesion was well visualized, being moderately dense in a predominantly fat-density background, and not too posterior for positioning. Stereotactic biopsy was performed, showing <abbr title="ductal carcinoma in situ">DCIS</abbr> with microinvasion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150205&amp;id=fig9c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150205/asset/images/large/rg.2016150205.fig10a.jpeg" height="477" width="758" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span>. Clinically suspicious palpable finding in the right lower inner quadrant in a 40-year-old high-risk patient. <b>(a)</b> US image shows a correlative discrete focal area of heterogeneous tissue (arrows, cursors) that was separate from the central cone of breast tissue. The patient had undergone negative mammography (not shown) several months previously. Although a benign cause such as focal fibrocystic change or <abbr title="pseudoangiomatous stromal hyperplasia">PASH</abbr> was favored, an infiltrative malignancy could have a similar US appearance. Given the clinical finding and the patient’s risk factors, the radiologist recommended MR imaging. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced fat-suppressed image shows focal nonmass enhancement correlating with the palpable finding (arrow). In this case, MR imaging did not contribute to diagnostic specificity because most of the possible benign causes for the clinical and US finding (focal fibrocystic change, hormonally mediated parenchymal changes, <abbr title="pseudoangiomatous stromal hyperplasia">PASH</abbr>) would show enhancement at MR imaging. Excisional biopsy yielded a diagnosis of <abbr title="pseudoangiomatous stromal hyperplasia">PASH</abbr>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150205&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150205/asset/images/large/rg.2016150205.fig10b.jpeg" height="942" width="569" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span>. Clinically suspicious palpable finding in the right lower inner quadrant in a 40-year-old high-risk patient. <b>(a)</b> US image shows a correlative discrete focal area of heterogeneous tissue (arrows, cursors) that was separate from the central cone of breast tissue. The patient had undergone negative mammography (not shown) several months previously. Although a benign cause such as focal fibrocystic change or <abbr title="pseudoangiomatous stromal hyperplasia">PASH</abbr> was favored, an infiltrative malignancy could have a similar US appearance. Given the clinical finding and the patient’s risk factors, the radiologist recommended MR imaging. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced fat-suppressed image shows focal nonmass enhancement correlating with the palpable finding (arrow). In this case, MR imaging did not contribute to diagnostic specificity because most of the possible benign causes for the clinical and US finding (focal fibrocystic change, hormonally mediated parenchymal changes, <abbr title="pseudoangiomatous stromal hyperplasia">PASH</abbr>) would show enhancement at MR imaging. Excisional biopsy yielded a diagnosis of <abbr title="pseudoangiomatous stromal hyperplasia">PASH</abbr>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150205&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150205/asset/images/large/rg.2016150205.fig11a.jpeg" height="881" width="546" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span>. Focal asymmetry in a 63-year-old woman. <b>(a, b)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <b>(a)</b> and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(b)</b> views show a focal asymmetry (arrow), persistent on spot compression views (not shown) but negative at US (not shown). MR imaging was recommended. <b>(c)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced T1-weighted fat-suppressed MR image shows a correlative area (arrow) of apparent fibroglandular tissue with minimal enhancement, similar to the degree of enhancement of fibroglandular tissue in the breast. The lesion was assessed as benign. Four years later, the patient underwent biopsy of the lesion due to subtle mammographic changes. Histopathologic analysis showed stage 1 invasive ductal cancer.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150205&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150205/asset/images/large/rg.2016150205.fig11b.jpeg" height="881" width="570" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span>. Focal asymmetry in a 63-year-old woman. <b>(a, b)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <b>(a)</b> and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(b)</b> views show a focal asymmetry (arrow), persistent on spot compression views (not shown) but negative at US (not shown). MR imaging was recommended. <b>(c)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced T1-weighted fat-suppressed MR image shows a correlative area (arrow) of apparent fibroglandular tissue with minimal enhancement, similar to the degree of enhancement of fibroglandular tissue in the breast. The lesion was assessed as benign. Four years later, the patient underwent biopsy of the lesion due to subtle mammographic changes. Histopathologic analysis showed stage 1 invasive ductal cancer.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150205&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150205/asset/images/large/rg.2016150205.fig11c.jpeg" height="881" width="736" aria-labelledby="fig11c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11c</span>. Focal asymmetry in a 63-year-old woman. <b>(a, b)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <b>(a)</b> and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(b)</b> views show a focal asymmetry (arrow), persistent on spot compression views (not shown) but negative at US (not shown). MR imaging was recommended. <b>(c)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced T1-weighted fat-suppressed MR image shows a correlative area (arrow) of apparent fibroglandular tissue with minimal enhancement, similar to the degree of enhancement of fibroglandular tissue in the breast. The lesion was assessed as benign. Four years later, the patient underwent biopsy of the lesion due to subtle mammographic changes. Histopathologic analysis showed stage 1 invasive ductal cancer.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150205&amp;id=fig11c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150205/asset/images/large/rg.2016150205.fig12a.jpeg" height="501" width="558" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span>. Equivocal architectural distortion in a 49-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Left <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> mammographic view shows only equivocal architectural distortion (arrow), which had an equivocal US correlate (not shown). <b>(b)</b> <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> magnification view also shows suspicious pleomorphic clustered calcifications (arrow) more posteriorly in the left breast. (They were also apparent on the <abbr title="mediolateral">ML</abbr> magnification view [not shown].) MR imaging was recommended to evaluate the equivocal one-view distortion before biopsy of the calcifications. <b>(c)</b> MIP MR image shows marked background enhancement without a correlative focal lesion. At excision of calcifications, the patient had multifocal invasive ductal and lobular carcinoma with greater than 10 tumor foci ranging from 0.5 to 0.8 cm in surrounding tissue.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150205&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150205/asset/images/large/rg.2016150205.fig12b.jpeg" height="501" width="455" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span>. Equivocal architectural distortion in a 49-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Left <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> mammographic view shows only equivocal architectural distortion (arrow), which had an equivocal US correlate (not shown). <b>(b)</b> <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> magnification view also shows suspicious pleomorphic clustered calcifications (arrow) more posteriorly in the left breast. (They were also apparent on the <abbr title="mediolateral">ML</abbr> magnification view [not shown].) MR imaging was recommended to evaluate the equivocal one-view distortion before biopsy of the calcifications. <b>(c)</b> MIP MR image shows marked background enhancement without a correlative focal lesion. At excision of calcifications, the patient had multifocal invasive ductal and lobular carcinoma with greater than 10 tumor foci ranging from 0.5 to 0.8 cm in surrounding tissue.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150205&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150205/asset/images/large/rg.2016150205.fig12c.jpeg" height="501" width="836" aria-labelledby="fig12c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12c</span>. Equivocal architectural distortion in a 49-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Left <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> mammographic view shows only equivocal architectural distortion (arrow), which had an equivocal US correlate (not shown). <b>(b)</b> <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> magnification view also shows suspicious pleomorphic clustered calcifications (arrow) more posteriorly in the left breast. (They were also apparent on the <abbr title="mediolateral">ML</abbr> magnification view [not shown].) MR imaging was recommended to evaluate the equivocal one-view distortion before biopsy of the calcifications. <b>(c)</b> MIP MR image shows marked background enhancement without a correlative focal lesion. At excision of calcifications, the patient had multifocal invasive ductal and lobular carcinoma with greater than 10 tumor foci ranging from 0.5 to 0.8 cm in surrounding tissue.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150205&amp;id=fig12c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150205/asset/images/large/rg.2016150205.fig13.jpeg" height="1043" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig13" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13</span>. Management algorithm for appropriate use of problem-solving MR imaging for mammographic lesions. For an equivocal lesion (*), if real, a finding would be considered suspicious (ie, developing asymmetry, architectural distortion).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150205&amp;id=fig13">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Sardanelli F, Melani E, Ottonello C, et al. Magnetic resonance imaging of the breast in characterizing positive or uncertain mammographic findings. <em>Cancer Detect Prev</em> 1998;22(1):39–42.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1046/j.1525-1500.1998.00005.x">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed">